story.title: Christmas in New York - Episode 1
story.storyDescription: The guy sitting next to me on the plane is terrified.
story.creator: web-uploader

author.bio: Digital Storyteller. Gryffindor Head Girl. Author of Beware the Scare, a short collection of spooky stories. II buy book: http://bit.ly/bewarethescare II watch trailer: http://bit.ly/bewarethescaretrailer II visit me: www.kaylaparent.com

messages.text: The guy sitting next to me on the plane is terrified.
Like, really terrified.
Breathing heavy…
Bouncing legs…
I’m pretty sure he’s going to wear holes in the armrests.
My first instinct is to comfort him.
But these days, I’m barely able to comfort myself.
So I look out the window and try to ignore him.
He, apparently, has other ideas.
Can I ask you a favor?
Is he talking to me?
I turn and his big brown eyes meet mine.
He smells like Christmas cookies.
Sure. What’s up?
He wipes the sweat on his brow.
I have this fear of flying…
And I think I’d feel better if I could see out the window.
Do you mind switching seats with me?
He looks really nervous, as if he thinks I’m going to say no.
But I don’t care if he wants to switch seats.
In fact, I don’t care about much these days.
No, I don’t mind.
He blows out a relieved breath and holds out his hand.
Thank you so much…um?
I shake his hand.
Amy.
Amy, thank you. I’m Josh.
What should have been a simple seat swap takes a bit longer than necessary.
He’s a large, well-built guy…
And I have to maneuver around a huge backpack full of Christmas cookies at his feet.
Ahhh…
That explains the smell.
Just as I settle into my new seat, I hear his voice again.
Want one?
He’s holding up a tree-shaped cookie.
No thanks.
Come on, as a thank you.
They’re airport brand but still good.
I shake my head.
I don’t want anything to do with Christmas this year.
Not even one delicious smelling cookie.
I close my eyes and he seems to get the hint.
But then I hear him again when we’re taking off.
He’s mumbling to himself.
The odds of being in a plane crash are 1 in 11 million.
The plane begins to pick up speed.
My eyes are still closed, but I can feel the tension radiating off him.
And over 8 million people fly every day!
The plane lifts off the ground…
His breathing gets heavier…
And then, he does the last thing I expect.
He grabs my hand and squeezes.
The contact sends a jolt through my body.
Not because he’s a stranger…
Or because it takes me by surprise…
But because I haven’t been touched by anyone in over three months.
Not since my parents died.
After their funeral, I isolated myself.
And his touch makes me realize how lonely I am.
Suddenly, I feel overwhelmed.
My breathing gets heavy…
And my face scrunches as I try to hold back my tears.
This is going to be my first Christmas without my parents.
And since spending it at home would be torture…
I went to the airport this morning and asked for a ticket across the country.
So now, here I am.
On my way to New York City.
Far, far away from painful memories.
Josh suddenly lets go of my hand.
I’m sorry.
I didn’t hurt you, did I?
My eyes spring open.
What?
He motions to my face.
You look like you’re in pain.
Did I squeeze your hand too hard?
Oh…no.
It’s not that.
He leans down and grabs a cookie.
Then what is it?
I stare at him for a moment.
Is he serious?
It’s nothing.
His eyes roam my face.
He must see something there…
Because he immediately changes the subject.
Sitting by the window does help.
With my fear of flying. This is my first time on a plane, actually.
But so far so good.
So far so good?
He’s two seconds away from a panic attack.
At least I can say that Phase 1 is now complete.
Don’t ask, Amy.
Don’t even ask.
What’s Phase 1?
Damn it. I asked.
Josh grabs ANOTHER cookie.
I give him a once over.
How on earth does he stay so fit?
I’m on a mission to face all my fears.
It’s my Christmas present to myself.
Phase 1 was getting on a plane.
Don’t ask.
Don’t ask!
So there are other phases?
He nods.
Phase 2 is crowds.
And Phase 3 is heights.
I thought New York would be the perfect place to overcome all three.
That’s why I’m taking this trip.
Plus, I’ve never been there.
Two birds, one stone.
Okayyyy…
This guy is odd.
I still don’t really get it.
Why would you want to spend the holiday doing things that scare you?
He smiles, and it transforms his face. He becomes seriously hot.
He seems like the type of guy that smiles all the time.
Because living in fear is no way to live.
And besides, my plans kinda uhh…they fell through.
So I wanted to do something fun and different.
I figured this was the perfect time.
Yup.
Josh is still super odd.
And possibly masochistic.
I close my eyes again, hoping he’ll just stop talking to me.
What about you?
Visiting family in New York?
My whole body tenses.
Again, tears spring up in my eyes at the mention of family…
But I force them back.
No way I’m telling him the truth. He’s a complete stranger.
No. This is a solo trip for me.
My family is umm…my plans fell through too.
I clear my throat.
I’ve never been to New York either.
Thought it would be fun.
I see.
The plane jolts again.
And the pilot’s voice comes over the loudspeaker…
Warning us of turbulence.
Josh grips the armrests.
Can I ask you for another favor?
I eye him warily.
Okay…
Can you just…talk to me for a while?
I don’t care what it’s about.
He winces as the plane jolts.
I could use the distraction.
Ugh.
It’s the last thing I want to do.
I’m not in the mood to be social.
But then I remember something my mom used to say to me…
“No one is useless in this world who lightens the burdens of another.”
So I take a deep breath.
And I start talking.
My name’s Amy.
I’m from Walla Walla Washington…
Thinking, I eye his bag of cookies.
And I think salty snacks are way better than sweet ones.
He reacts exactly as I hoped he would.
Are you kidding?!
Sweet trumps salty any day.
I pretend to take offense, then keep talking.
I tell him about my likes and dislikes…
About my hobbies and my career goals.
In turn, he tells me some embarrassing stories.
And shows me photos of his friends and family.
I find out that he lives in a town near mine and went to a rival high school.
Time passes.
Before we know it, the plane lands.
Josh lets out a huge sigh of relief.
Thank you so much, Amy.
I don’t know what I would have done without you.
A part of me wants to thank him too.
Because he also distracted me.
But then the pilot’s voice comes over the loudspeaker again…
And he wishes us and our families a Happy Holiday.
Just like that, my mood plummets.
I think Josh notices, but thankfully, he doesn’t say anything this time.
We exit together and say our goodbyes at baggage claim.
It was nice to meet you, Amy Baker.
Thanks again for making Phase 1 bearable.
He goes in for a hug, but I stop him.
I can barely stomach the touch of a familiar hand…
Let alone a hug.
He takes my rejection in stride.
Nice to meet you, Josh Willard.
Enjoy New York.
And good luck completing your mission.
He grins, and I feel my stomach flip.
When he smiles, he’s just so handsome.
If I were the old Amy…
I would have turned up the charm.
But the old Amy is gone.
Just like that, I’m all alone.
I sit myself down in a chair, wondering what the hell I’m going to do next.
Why did I decide to come to New York?
I don’t know my way around.
I don’t know anyone.
Heck, I don’t even have a place to stay!
Plus, the airport is full of happy families.
Some reuniting.
Some bright-faced, ready for Christmas in the city.
And here I am, in one of the busiest places in the world…
Completely alone.
I put my head in my hands…
And just sit there.
I don’t know for how long.
Maybe ten minutes.
Maybe an hour.
But finally, I feel someone sit beside me.
And he smells like Christmas cookies.
Josh.
He doesn’t say anything, but I can feel him watching me.
When I work up the courage to meet his gaze…
His eyes are softer than I have ever seen them.
He grabs my hand this time.
What are you afraid of, Amy?
I don’t want to answer.
I just want to run.
After all, I’ve been running from everything else.
But I feel pinned down by the weight of his stare.
I can’t…be alone.
He nods once, and then stands up.
My hand is still in his, so the movement forces me up too.
Alright then. You’re coming with me.
Wait, what?!
Coming with you where?!
I don’t even know you!
He rolls his eyes playfully.
You know enough about me. Come on, Amy…
It’s Christmas Eve morning and we’re in New York!
Let’s have a day!
He cracks that wide smile again.
You know, one of those wild, wonderful days…
Where the whole world is at your fingertips!
I bite my lip, unsure.
Because honestly, what else do I have to do with myself?
And he looks so excited.
My Christmas Eve tradition is to watch holiday movies with my father…
To bake Christmas treats with my mother.
And now this guy who smells like Christmas is right before me…
Telling me that I still deserve a holiday…
Even though all the other signs tell me that I don’t.
The thought sends a pang through my chest.
Alright. Let’s have a day.
He shocks me by fist-pumping the air.
His enthusiasm is a bit jarring.
Is this the way he is naturally?
Or is it all the sugar he consumed on the plane?
During the taxi to Manhattan, I realize it’s all him.
He’s like a big kid in a candy store.
Isn’t that the most amazing skyline you’ve ever seen?
And look how tall the buildings are, wow!
The only thing that would make today more perfect would be some snow.
I crinkle my nose.
Snow?
Mhmm.
Snow means a fresh start.
My throat scratches with new tears. I just nod.
At Josh’s insistence, we get dropped off in one of the busiest parts of the city.
Times Square.
Are you kidding me?
Josh shakes his head.
Of course not! This is Phase 2.
Sink or swim.
From the moment we’re let out of the taxi…it’s pandemonium.
There are people everywhere, going every which way.
Josh grabs my hand.
When I look over at him, he looks completely shell-shocked.
I drag him to the edge of the sidewalk so he can lean against a building.
Are you okay?
He shakes his head.
Not yet.
He takes a deep breath.
And another one.
And then he steels his spine.
But if I can face one of the busiest places in the world…
I can face anything.
His eyes dart around.
And then we just stand in place…
I realize Josh may need a push in the right direction.
Just like he did on the plane.
So I lean beside him, against the building.
My dad used to travel to New York all the time for work.
He loved it. He wanted to take my mom and me here for the holidays.
He used to say, “There’s Christmas, and then there’s Christmas in New York.”
I didn’t mean to reveal that whole story.
And with the way Josh is looking at me…
Maybe I revealed too much.
I shrug, feeling embarrassed.
But then that smile returns to Josh’s face…
And he pulls me onto the busy sidewalk.
Well, then I’ve got to give you a Christmas in New York.
After that, Josh seems calmer.
I can’t help but feel proud.
And a part of me is envious too.
I wish I could face my problems head-on like he does.
Or be honest with someone about what’s bothering me.
We walk the length of Times Square and go into a few stores.
I scoff when he buys a huge bag of candy…
Balk when he makes me take a photo with the naked cowboy…
And finally smile when he buys me a rose from a street vendor.
The grin feels foreign on my face.
Josh’s eyes lock on my mouth.
Hey, look at that.
What?
I knew you had a beautiful smile.
The compliment is so sweet, I let loose another truth.
It’s been a while.
I can tell he wants to push the subject…
But thankfully, he lets it go.
We just walk in stride, up Broadway and into Central Park.
Past the pond where black ducks are diving into the water.
I eye them sadly.
Don’t you think they’re bothered by the cold?
Josh doesn’t answer.
Instead he reaches out his arms slowly…
I know he’s going for the hug…
And this time, I let him hold me.
I relax into it, just for a second — before I pull away.
I forgot how warm it is inside someone’s arms.
Josh doesn’t push me to say anything.
Instead, we finish strolling through Central Park in silence.
And he suddenly freezes in front of the Plaza Hotel.
Josh?
Are you okay?
He pauses for a few moments…
And then yells so loud that I jump out of my skin.
KEVIN!
YOU SPENT $967 ON ROOM SERVICE?!
My mouth drops open.
A few people stop to stare…
But most just walk by, apparently immune to such outbursts.
When Josh turns to me his eyes are twinkling.
I look up at the building in front of me and slap my hand over my mouth.
I finally get his joke.
Oh my god!
This is the hotel from Home Alone 2!
Yup.
Let’s go inside and see if they sell any of those sweets he was eating!
I laugh at Josh’s dependable sweet tooth.
It’s like his stomach is a bottomless pit.
But since it’s nearing lunch and I also need to eat…
We sample a few savory bites from the food vendors inside the hotel.
And even as we sit eating amid crowds of holiday shoppers…
Josh seemed so relaxed.
So, is Phase 2 going well?
Josh looks at me thoughtfully.
You know, with the crowds?
I think I can officially say Phase 2 is complete.
He gives me a sheepish look.
I wasn’t always like this, you know.
I got lost at a carnival when I was five.
Separated from my parents.
It was so crowded.
They found me half an hour later…
But I think it traumatized me.
I gave him a sad smile.
And why are you scared of flying?
He shrugs.
I’m a mechanical engineer.
So I understand everything that could go wrong on one of those things.
I shake my head quickly, holding out my hands.
Don’t tell me!
Josh winks.
I won’t.
Look, I know this is pretty pathetic.
Being afraid of everything.
There’s a brief silence before he continues.
You know, my ex hated it about me.
She broke up with me a few weeks ago.
That’s why my Christmas plans really got cancelled.
We were going to spend the holiday together.
Josh…
Don’t. Really. You don’t have to feel bad.
Anyway, she’s the reason I came out here.
Why I’m facing my fears.
And I feel like a new man now.
Honestly. This is the happiest I’ve been in a while.
I think that says a lot about our relationship.
I take his hands in both of mine.
I think it surprises both of us, that I’m initiating contact.
Well, I’m proud of you.
You know, for today.
I think what you’re doing is really brave.
He grins and his eyes roam my face.
He’s done that a lot today.
I wonder what he sees when he looks at me.
Thank you.
But be proud of me when I finish Phase 3, okay?
I stare at him blankly.
Heights, remember?
I thought we could go to the Empire State Building.
I hear they have an observation deck and everything.
Oh, that’s right. Let’s do it!
Josh laughs at my sudden enthusiasm.
Alright then. Empire State Building, here we come!
I laugh and we make our way over, holding hands the whole time.
It feels natural.
And I feel lighter than I have in months.
Once we get to the Empire State Building…
Nervous Josh comes back.
We both stand at the entrance and look up.
You know, maybe I should start out with something smaller?
Something with just three or four stories?
You have no idea how many structural mistakes there could be in that building.
I squeeze his hand.
Oh no, you don’t! Don’t go calculating all the ways this could go wrong.
Josh flashes a guilty smile that looks more like a grimace.
I pivot, trying a new tactic.
You know, my mom used to have a sign on her classroom door that read…
“There is no top. There are always further heights to reach.”
Josh and I turn to each other at the same time.
And just like on the plane…
Just like in the crowd at Times Square…
I can see Josh gathering courage from my words.
He nods.
Good thing I wore my walking shoes.
And then we start to walk.
Up 102 floors.
Following crowds of people…
For a solid hour.
And the whole time, we don’t let go of each other’s hands once.
When we get to the door…
The one that leads out to the upper deck…
He hesitates.
You can do this, Josh.
One step out this door…
And your mission will be complete.
His whole body is shaking…
But he’s the one who pushes the door open.
And he’s the one who leads us outside.
As if by fate, there’s an opening for us by the edge of the rooftop.
We walk toward it…
And then there we are.
Gazing down at one of the greatest cities in the world.
It’s mesmerizing.
I close my eyes, feeling the wind blow through my hair.
Free…
I feel free.
I open my eyes, hoping Josh does too.
He’s staring at the view below with wonder.
His awe-filled eyes meet mine.
They roam my face again, warming me from the inside out.
Beautiful.
I’m not sure if he’s talking about me or the city…
But in that moment, I don’t care.
It could be both. It could be either.
We enjoy the view for a few more minutes…
And then I remember something my dad used to say.
“One of the greatest discoveries a man makes…
“Is to find he can do what he was afraid he couldn’t do.”
A hum of agreement sounds from Josh’s throat.
Another quote from your parents?
Yeah.
My dad.
They seem like awesome people.
Your parents.
My heart stutters.
But it’s there, beating in my chest.
And just like Josh was able to face his fears…
I know that I can talk about my parents.
Because I’m with him. This is Josh.
They were.
My parents WERE awesome people.
Josh stills.
I can feel him watching me.
I’m sorry.
What happ—
Actually, I don’t want to talk about it.
Just like that, my courage fails me.
Luckily, Josh drops the subject.
A half an hour later, we make our way back down to street level.
We’re quiet the entire way down.
Across the street, I spy a bakery.
I force myself to smile.
How about a sweet to celebrate your victory?
For completing all the phases?
Amy…
Continuing to feign cheerfulness, I interrupt him.
I don’t want to ruin his moment.
Oh look!
They have cannolis.
Didn’t you say those were your favorite?
He blows out a breath and nods.
Accepting that I don’t want to talk about anything.
I’m relieved.
I’m hanging by a thread as it is…
And I know I can’t actually stomach a conversation about my parents.
It would shred me to pieces.
We walk into the bakery…
And I see it.
A sign for rum cake.
“Christmas Rum Cake. Just like mom used to make.”
I suck in a breath.
What’s wrong?
The emotions I’ve been holding in all day rush up my throat.
I let out a sob so loud, everyone in the store turns to me at once.
My hand slaps over my mouth.
And I run out the door.
I can hear Josh calling me.
But I can’t stop.
My head is buzzing.
And my world is closing in from all sides.
Amy!
Stop running!
I stop short.
Put my head in my hands…
And cry my eyes out.
I cry over the unfairness of it all.
I cry because it’s my first Christmas without them…
And I cry because I flew across the country like a crazy person—
Completely alone.
But then Josh’s arms are around me.
And I know…
I’m not alone.
He’s rubbing my back whispering soothing words.
I sniffle, and burrow into his chest.
And it feels so good to be held.
My mom and I used to bake rum cake every Christmas.
Josh grips me tighter.
I miss them.
He presses his lips against the top of my head.
What happened?
They got into a car accident three months ago.
They…didn’t make it.
Josh holds me even tighter.
He strokes my back as I continue to tell him about that night.
About the following three months.
And how I ended up here in New York.
By the end of the story, I feel so much lighter…
Lighter than I ever have since their deaths.
It’s almost like I’m at the top of the Empire State Building again…
Free.
The feeling is impossible, and I look into Josh’s eyes…
Knowing that he helped me get here.
To this point of acceptance.
Thank you, Josh.
For today.
I don’t know what I would have done if I hadn’t met you.
Josh bends down so we’re at eye-level with one another.
I feel the same way about you, Amy. You were my angel today.
You made one of the scariest days of my life bright.
Suddenly I realized how close we’re standing.
And I think he realizes it too, because his arms twitch around me.
I can’t stop looking at him…
He can’t stop looking at me…
And I wonder if he’s going to kiss me.
Here, in New York City.
In the middle of the loud, bustling sidewalk.
His hand comes up to cup the back of my head…
He starts to lean toward me…
And my heart hammers furiously in my chest.
Meanwhile…
A woman races down the block because she’s late for a meeting.
Who makes their employees work on Christmas Eve anyway?
Her mood couldn’t be worse.
She feels like Scrooge, glaring at everyone and anyone who gets in her way.
Just as she’s about to cross the street to her office…
She spots them.
It’s a young couple…
Entwined together, gazing at one another in adoration.
The woman runs her hands through his hair…
Bringing his lips down to hers.
And they share a passionate kiss.
The businesswoman stops.
She’s never seen something so all-consuming and intimate in her life.
A few minutes later, she crosses the street.
But before she walks into her building…
She puts her hand out, letting the first airy flakes of snow fall into her palm.
And her heart feels light, too.
